Lynx population size and hunting1

Hudsonâs Bay Company is one of the oldest corporations in Canada. It still operates retail stores across Canada today but, for much of history, it was a fur trading business. One of the animals targeted by fur trappers in the 1700âs and 1800âs was the lynx. The number of pelts obtained by the Hudsonâs Bay Company each year between 1752 and 1819 is in the LynxPopulation.csv dataset. Given the intense hunting, one might predict a decline in the population size over time. Read in the data and perform a linear regression predicting number of pelts by year using lm().

#FIXME

LL <- read_csv("../Data/LynxPopulation.csv",
               show_col_types = FALSE)

mod <- lm(pelts ~ year, data=LL)
summary(mod)

Summarize your conclusions regarding the effect of fur trapping over time on lynx population size.

The slope of the coefficient for year is -30.6 which is significantly different from 0. We woudl conclude that the number of lynx pelts decreases by about 30 per year. If the Hudsonâs Bay Company had been around at year 0, it would have collected over 56,000 pelts.

Letâs construct a plot displaying the linear regression results. Plot pelt number versus year and use geom_point() and geom_smooth(method="lm"). By default geom_smooth() with lm, will use the formula y ~ x. You can make this explicit by adding formula = y ~ x to the statement.

#FIXME

LL %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, pelts)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ x)

Do you notice anything in the plot that suggests there might be an issue with using linear regression to analyze these data?

There are some low years that seem to have similar values, in clusters of threes and fours. This is particularly noticeable in teh years leading up to 1820.

Because these data were collected over time, letâs connect the points so we can see trends over time more clearly. Add geom_line() to your plot to do this.

#FIXME

LL %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, pelts)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ x)

Does connecting the points change your conclusions about the appropriateness of linear regression to address your question about population decline? Do you have any ideas of better ways to analyze these data?

Now it is clear that there are cycles of number of lynx pelts. There is very obvious correlation year-to-year in the number of pelts and these cycles go up and down. The cycles seem to rise for a few years and then fall to a few low years (noted above). These data do not meet the assumptions of OLS regression: the points are not independent of one another. If we looked at the residuals, they probably would have apparent structure and not look like the errors are normally distributed. We would need a model that somehow can account for the autocorrelation between years and that can model the cycles, while also somehow looking for the change over time. Such models exist but are beyond the scope of this problem set.

If you had plotted the data as a first step, how do you think that would affect your next steps and conclusions?

Hopefully, we would have seen the patterns in the data and not moved straight to the linear model.

Peacock hoots

Male peacocks give a hoot call when approaching a female to copulate. Sometimes males will hoot even when a female is not present. Dakin and Montgomerie2 hypothesized that males might perform these solitary hoots as a dishonest signal implying a copulation attempt to attract females. You can see an example hoot here

The data they collected consists of female presence before and after 131 solo hoot calls. This data is in the PeacockHoots.csv file. Load this data.

#FIXME

PP <- read_csv("../Data/PeacockHoots.csv",
               show_col_types = FALSE)
PP

What ideas do you have for the type of plot you might want to make that could communicate whether female presence increases following single hoots?

The data is just female absence or presence. So we would like to visualize the counts of these data across the treatments.

Below is a figure from the paper looking at female presence before and after hoots and two other types of calls.

Examine the dataset you just loaded. Is there a better way to present these data?

Use a bar chart to show the counts. Or just make a table, because itâs not that many numbers.

One way you might want to plot counts is to use a bar chart (see Lecture 1.3). Letâs make a bar chart showing female presence and absence pre and post hoot using geom_bar(). This will allow us to see the actual female counts rather than a proportion. The authors performed this study at multiple zoos so we will also split the data by Place. First weâll need to wrangle our data.

Do the following to create a new tibble that has counts for female presence and absence for each location both pre and post hoot:

  • Group the data by both Place and PrePost
  • Create two new variables, Present and Absent that contain the total number of observations for a present female (coded as 1) and an absent female (coded as 0).
  • Create a single id, Place_Time that codes for both location and pre vs.Â post separated by an underscore
  • Use pivot_longer to make a single Presence column denoting Present or Absent and a Counts column holding the count of observations

The first few rows of your resulting tibble should look like this:

# A tibble: 12 Ã 3
   Place_Time Presence Counts
   <chr>      <chr>     <dbl>
 1 CA_Post    Present      10
 2 CA_Post    Absent       30
 3 CA_Pre     Present       4
 4 CA_Pre     Absent       31
#FIXME

PPcts <- PP %>% 
  group_by(Place, PrePost) %>% 
  summarize("Present" = sum(FemaleVisit.5m), 
            "Absent" = sum(FemaleVisit.5m==0),
            .groups = "drop") %>%
  unite("Place_Time", Place:PrePost, sep="_") %>%
  pivot_longer(!Place_Time, names_to = "Presence", values_to="Counts")

Now we are ready to make our bar chart with Place_Time on the x-axis and Counts on the y-axis. Use fill to show female presence and absence. Donât forget to use stat = "identity" to plot the raw counts. Try the plot with and without position = "dodge" to decide between stacked or grouped bars. Also use scale_fill_manual() and choose two colors you like for your plot.

#FIXME

PPcts %>% ggplot(aes(x = Place_Time, Counts, fill = Presence)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("steelblue", "darkred")) 
PPcts %>% ggplot(aes(x = Place_Time, Counts, fill = Presence)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("steelblue", "darkred"))

What are the pros and cons of this plots we just made compared to the one in the paper (shown above)? What other changes might you want to make to improve your plot even more?

A positive is that, viewed this way, we can see that there were a lot more observations in the CA group, both pre- and post-. The patterns look similar across the groups though. The drawback is that itâs very hard to compare proportions between treatments, even in the stacked bar chart. We can say that visually they look similar, but there is no easy way to compare the proportions like there is with the plot from the paper.

Trade-offs in sand crickets

When Dr.Â King was a graduate student, she collected data on flight muscle mass and ovary mass in sand crickets reared on different diets 3 This dataset is called Kingetal2011.csv. Read this data in. The diet treatment is in a column called Food, flight muscle mass is DLM_Mass and ovary mass is Ovary_Mass. There is also information about family ids, wing morphology, and total mass.

#FIXME

CC <- read_csv("../Data/Kingetal2011.csv",
               show_col_types = FALSE)

If we are interested in the trade-off between flight muscle mass and ovary mass, we might wish to perform a correlation and/or use a linear regression model with these data. However, weâve learned it is a good idea to plot the data before beginning analysis so letâs do that. Make a scatterplot with DLM_Mass on the y-axis and Ovary_Mass on the x-axis using geom_point(). Color by Food treatment.

#FIXME

CC %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Ovary_Mass, y = DLM_Mass, color = Food)) +
  geom_point()

Do you see any issues with the dataset you want to resolve before moving ahead?

There are some DLM masses that are about 10x larger than they should be. This is probably a data entry error. Also one of the food treatments is MED and should probably have been Med.

Correct or drop any problematic data points as you wish.

What do you notice about this dataset from this plot?

There seems to be a negative association between the two variables overall (i.e., a tradeoff between flight muscle mass and ovary mass, as predicted). Itâs not clear if this pattern is consistent across all the treatments. The AD does seem to show it clearly. There are also a lot of points that seem to be at zero DLM mass. We should probably deal with those somehow in any statistical analysis.

To try out some different geoms, letâs first make a boxplot of the organ masses for with food treatments plotted separately. If you want to plot both organs on one plot, youâll need to pivot_longer() to create a column for Organ with the organ id and another column with Mass that holds the values. Do this and then use geom_boxplot() to make a boxplot of masses with the organ types grouped together and food treatment on the x-axis. Only include DLM and Ovary mass.

#FIXME

CC_long <- pivot_longer(CC,
                        cols = contains("Mass"),
                        names_to = "Organ",
                        values_to = "Mass")

CC_long %>%
  filter(Organ %in% c("DLM_Mass", "Ovary_Mass")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Food, y = Mass, fill = Organ)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Because the masses are on pretty different scales, letâs instead try out making two separate density plots using geom_density() for each organ (DLM and ovary), with food treatment indicated by color.
